Some (not exhaustive) components of systemd are:

- kernel-install โ to automatically move kernels and their respective initramfs images to the boot partition;
- systemd-analyze(1) โ may be used to determine boot-up performance, statistics and retrieve other state and tracing information, and to verify the correctness of unit files. It is also used to access special functions useful for advanced debugging.
- systemd-boot โ simple UEFI boot manager;
- systemd-creds โ to securely store and retrieve credentials used by systemd units;
- systemd-cryptenroll โ Enroll PKCS#11, FIDO2, TPM2 token/devices to LUKS2 encrypted volumes;
- systemd-firstboot โ basic system setting initialization before first boot;
- systemd-homed โ portable human-user accounts;
- systemd-logind(8) โ session management;
- systemd-networkd โ network configuration management;
- systemd-nspawn โ light-weight namespace container;
- systemd-repart โ creates partition tables, adds or grows partitions;
- systemd-resolved โ network name resolution;
- systemd-run(1) / run0(1) โ Temporarily and interactively acquire elevated or different privileges.
- systemd-stub(7) โ a UEFI boot stub used for creating unified kernel images;
- systemd-sysusers(8) โ creates system users and groups and adds users to groups at package installation or boot time;
- systemd-timesyncd โ system time synchronization across the network;
- systemd/Journal โ system logging;
- systemd/Timers โ monotonic or realtime timers for controlling .service files or events, reasonable alternative to cron.
